---
import Layout from '../layouts/BlogPost.astro';
---

<Layout
	title="Grey Failure Detector Demo"
	description="Interactive demonstration of grey failure detection in distributed systems ‚Äî built from AWS Lambda scale experience"
	pubDate={new Date('February 16 2026')}
>
	<p class="lead">
		An interactive visualization that demonstrates why traditional health checks miss the failures 
		that hurt users most. Built from real experience managing health systems at AWS Lambda scale (~1M instances).
	</p>

	<div class="demo-container">
		<iframe 
			src="/demos/grey-failure-detector.html" 
			width="100%" 
			height="800px"
			frameborder="0"
			style="border: 1px solid #e5e7eb; border-radius: 8px; box-shadow: 0 4px 6px -1px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1);"
			title="Grey Failure Detector Interactive Demo">
		</iframe>
	</div>

	<div class="demo-info">
		<h2>üéØ What This Teaches</h2>
		
		<p><strong>Grey Failure:</strong> When a system appears healthy to monitoring but performs poorly for actual users.</p>
		
		<p><strong>The Problem:</strong> Traditional health checks are binary (healthy/unhealthy) but real-world performance exists on a spectrum.</p>
		
		<p><strong>The Solution:</strong> Statistical monitoring that compares node performance against baseline metrics.</p>

		<h2>üéÆ How to Use</h2>
		<ol>
			<li><strong>Watch the baseline</strong> ‚Äî Observe healthy nodes processing requests</li>
			<li><strong>Select a node</strong> ‚Äî Click on any node in the cluster view</li>
			<li><strong>Inject failure</strong> ‚Äî Choose failure type and intensity, then inject</li>
			<li><strong>Compare detection</strong> ‚Äî Watch how traditional vs statistical monitoring responds</li>
			<li><strong>Observe the gap</strong> ‚Äî Traditional health checks stay green while users suffer</li>
		</ol>

		<h2>üìä Real-World Context</h2>
		<blockquote>
			<p>
				"At AWS Lambda scale managing ~1M instances, grey failures caused more customer impact 
				than complete outages because they went undetected for hours while traditional monitoring 
				showed 'all systems green'."
			</p>
		</blockquote>

		<p>
			This demo simulates the core concepts behind the statistical outlier detection systems 
			used in production cloud infrastructure at companies like AWS, Google, and Microsoft.
		</p>

		<h2>üß† Key Concepts Demonstrated</h2>
		
		<div class="concepts-grid">
			<div class="concept">
				<h3>‚ùå Traditional Health Checks</h3>
				<ul>
					<li><strong>Binary logic:</strong> Healthy or Unhealthy only</li>
					<li><strong>Simple checks:</strong> TCP/HTTP connectivity test</li>
					<li><strong>Blind spot:</strong> Misses performance degradation</li>
					<li><strong>Slow detection:</strong> 30+ seconds typical</li>
				</ul>
			</div>
			
			<div class="concept">
				<h3>‚úÖ Grey Failure Detection</h3>
				<ul>
					<li><strong>Multi-dimensional:</strong> Performance analysis across metrics</li>
					<li><strong>Statistical baseline:</strong> Compares against cluster performance</li>
					<li><strong>Early detection:</strong> Catches partial degradation quickly</li>
					<li><strong>Fast response:</strong> 2-5 seconds typical</li>
				</ul>
			</div>
		</div>

		<h2>üîß Technical Details</h2>
		
		<p><strong>Built with:</strong> React 18 + TypeScript, Framer Motion animations, Zustand state management, Tailwind CSS styling</p>
		
		<p><strong>Failure Types Simulated:</strong></p>
		<ul>
			<li><strong>Latency Spike:</strong> Node responds but 5-10x slower than baseline</li>
			<li><strong>Error Rate:</strong> Node drops percentage of requests randomly</li>
			<li><strong>Partial Failure:</strong> Mix of increased latency and dropped requests</li>
		</ul>

		<div class="links">
			<h2>üîó Links</h2>
			<ul>
				<li><a href="/demos/grey-failure-detector.html" target="_blank">üöÄ Open Demo in New Tab</a></li>
				<li><a href="https://github.com/gpclaws/grey-failure-detector" target="_blank">üíª View Source Code</a></li>
				<li><a href="/demos/grey-failure-detector.html" download="grey-failure-detector.html">üì• Download Standalone Version</a></li>
			</ul>
		</div>

		<p class="closing">
			<em>
				"The best way to understand distributed systems is to build them, break them, and monitor them. 
				This demo lets you do all three safely."
			</em>
		</p>
	</div>
</Layout>

<style>
